text: The mood around the Emirates on Saturday afternoon should be optimistic yet many of the grumbles of recent seasons could be evident given Arsenal's alarming lack of transfer activity over the past few months. This was meant to be the summer when the club spent big yet, as things stand, Arsène Wenger's only fresh recruit is the young French attacker Yaya Sanogo. In contrast, Aston Villa have been busy and, with Christian Benteke remaining in situ, Paul Lambert will be expecting his young side to have the maturity to avoid a repeat of last season's relegation fight. Sachin Nakrani

For all the distractions caused by you-know-who, Liverpool at least enter the campaign with goals in their team and an established style of play after one season with Brendan Rodgers. Daniel Sturridge is back from an ankle injury ahead of schedule and may start in place of Iago Aspas, who struggled against Celtic's physical defence in Dublin last weekend. Stoke, by contrast, begin life under Mark Hughes with the same attacking options that produced only 34 goals last season – a tally bettered by every team apart from relegated QPR – and searching for a new identity after the exit of Tony Pulis. Andy Hunter

Arguably one of the most intriguing ties of the weekend because of the wholesale changes that have taken place at both clubs this summer. Everton begin life under their new manager, Roberto Martínez, who is expected to adopt a different tactical approach to his predecessor, David Moyes. Norwich, meanwhile, have moved boldly in the transfer market and Chris Hughton could hand debuts to a number of new recruits including Gary Hooper and the Canaries' record signing, Ricky van Wolfswinkel. James Riach

Darren Bent, newly arrived at Fulham on loan from Aston Villa, is available to feature but the striker may not recognise his one former club. Paolo Di Canio, Sunderland's manager, says he has presided over a "complete revolution" this summer. Embracing much enhanced discipline and fitness it is intended to have given the team a "new identity" courtesy of more attractive football, played from the back and 10 new summer signings. Louise Taylor

Can David Moyes do it? Can he continue the work of Sir Alex Ferguson, who turned Manchester United into a trophy-greedy juggernaut? The answer is this Premier League season's must-see show. Whether the unhappy Wayne Rooney travels to the Liberty Stadium and is part of his matchday squad is a side issue. Moyes's prime focus is to leave south Wales unbeaten – victory would be a bonus. Jamie Jackson

The home side's manager, Steve Clarke, believes his side are "better and stronger" than the one that ended last season in eighth place but they may struggle unless new arrivals Nicolas Anelka and Matej Vydra can compensate for the loss of Romelu Lukaku. Southampton may field new signings Victor Wanyama and Dejan Lovren from the outset as Gastón Ramírez and Maya Yoshida both made long international trips in midweek. Rich Flower

Much has changed for both of these sides since Cardiff won 1-0 at Upton Park on the opening day of the Championship season two years ago. While Sam Allardyce led West Ham to 10th place last term, Cardiff have been promoted as champions and have spent heavily before their first ever Premier League campaign. West Ham, who lost four times at home last season, will be without the injured Andy Carroll but Stewart Downing will feature after his £6m signing from Liverpool. Jacob Steinberg

This is a game of returns: for José Mourinho to Stamford Bridge, and Steve Bruce and Hull to the Premier League. The visitors have never won in this corner of south-west London and, even bolstered by summer reinforcements, will arrive braced for an instant reminder of the gulf between the top two divisions. Chelsea have quietly added to their options, but Mourinho is the main attraction. He did not lose a home league game first time round. That sequence is likely to be prolonged. Dominic Fifield

Glory, glory be. Tottenham Hotspur have a match and so, for 90 minutes at least, the relentless Gareth Bale transfer saga can be pushed to one side. Unless, that is, the team lack pace, penetration and goals out of nothing. Then he will loom larger still, even as he stays away from Selhurst Park because of injury. Tottenham look to have too much for newly-promoted Palace but Ian Holloway's team will carry the fight. It should be fun. David Hytner

Manuel Pellegrini begins his tenure at Manchester City having declared himself "absolutely" ready for the Premier League following a calm pre-season. The serene Chilean, hired in part as a kind of anti-Roberto Mancini, acquired Fernandinho, Jesús Navas, Stevan Jovetic and Alvaro Negredo early in the window so has had all summer to integrate them, and himself, into the club. Against Newcastle, whose manager Alan Pardew has to contend with answering to the new director of football, Joe Kinnear, anything but victory would be a surprise. Jamie Jackson

As Liverpool's star striker remains suspended Aston Villa's continues to shine. Christian Benteke has scored three times in his side's opening two games, only adding to the sense that Paul Lambert pulled off a masterstroke by convincing the Belgian to stay put. Without Luis Suárez, Liverpool impressed in their victory over Stoke last week but they will want to be more clinical this time around. Sachin Nakrani

West Bromwich Albion's commanding start to last season must appear a world away to Steve Clarke. A 90th-minute home defeat on the opening day has been compounded by Nicolas Anelka going on indefinite compassionate leave following the sudden death of his agent, Eric Manasse. Shane Long assumes greater responsibility in an attack adjusting to life without Romelu Lukaku, while the on-loan Scott Sinclair could make his debut. Roberto Martínez takes his league bow as Everton manager at Goodison Park looking to build on last week's encouraging draw at Norwich, minus the costly defensive errors. Andy Hunter

The fresh sense of crisis surrounding Arsenal has been eased by their midweek win over Fenerbahce but there remains pressure on Arsène Wenger's side to win following their unexpected loss to Aston Villa. Fulham, who could hand a debut to Scott Parker, are not expected to triumph given they have won three of their previous 24 Premier League games against the visitors. Sophy Coombes-Roberts

Both teams go into the game looking for their first win of the season. New arrival Tom Huddlestone is likely to start for Hull as Steve Bruce looks for a side full of new recruits to get off to a good start in front of their own supporters. Norwich, meanwhile, will be hoping record signing Ricky van Wolfswinkel can replicate his goal-scoring impact against Everton last week. Sophy Coombes-Roberts

The good news for Alan Pardew is that former Newcastle striker Andy Carroll will not feature in a visiting side managed by Sam Allardyce. If Allardyce was one of the least popular previous occupants of Pardew's office at St James' Park, few on Tyneside underestimate the threat posed by West Ham. Particularly on an afternoon when Newcastle – with or without the unsettled Yohan Cabaye – need to exorcise Monday's 4-0 thrashing at Manchester City. Louise Taylor

These are exciting times on the south coast. The arrival of Pablo Osvaldo, signed for a record-breaking £14.6m from Roma, indicates the size of Southampton's ambition, although the Italy forward will do well to dislodge Rickie Lambert, who scored the winner at West Bromwich Albion last week. Sunderland, hoping for a repeat of last season's 1-0 win at St Mary's, are already under pressure after the 1-0 defeat by Fulham, and Paolo Di Canio needs a swift response from his players. Jacob Steinberg

Both teams suffered less-than-surprising defeats in their respective opening day games so will be hoping to use this match to put their first points on the board. In their last meeting Stoke won 4-1, but judging from their showing against Spurs Ian Holloway's men should put up a fight, and could include Jason Puncheon, who has arrived on loan from Southampton. Sophy Coombes-Roberts

Defeat at West Ham was not the best way for Cardiff City to prepare for the visit of Manuel Pellegrini's Manchester City, who beat Newcastle in the opening weekend's most impressive display. Yet a concern for the Chilean is his defence, where Vincent Kompany's groin injury leaves Joleon Lescott is the only match-fit centre-back. Saying that, most of the action should be at the other end of the pitch anyway, where Jesus Navas's blistering pace should help City to a successive win. Jamie Jackson

According to André Villas-Boas, "the body is tired but the mind is happy, absolutely", following Tottenham's 5-0 Europa League thumping of Dinamo Tbilisi, and Swansea are in similar mood. They, too, scored five in the competition, against Petrolul Ploiesti, albeit at home, helping them a little in terms of time not spent travelling. The mission for both clubs is to prove that Europe will not sap them. This fixture was tight last season and Villas-Boas is anticipating more of the same. David Hytner

José Mourinho has suggested Chelsea will make a third bid for Wayne Rooney following this match, in turn surely affecting David Moyes's thinking in regards to whether or not to select the unhappy striker. Should Rooney be picked from the start it will be interesting to see the reception he receives from a home crowd whose patience has been stretched by the will-he-won't-he-leave saga. Jamie Jackson

After their stunning win against Manchester City last week, Cardiff will be looking to maintain momentum against an Everton side that have drawn their opening two games of the season. The visitors have lacked a cutting edge and almost lost to Stevenage in the Capital One Cup in midweek. Uncertainty also surrounds the future of Leighton Baines and Marouane Fellaini. Charlotte Trundley

Both teams are still looking for their first win of the season, with Paolo Di Canio keen for Sunderland to kickstart their campaign in order to avoid last year's relegation worries. Ian Holloway, meanwhile, has bemoaned the lack of Crystal Palace's signings this summer but can hope one new arrival, Marouane Chamakh, is in confident mood after scoring at Stoke last week. Charlotte Trundley

Having suffered a shock defeat to Cardiff, Manchester City will want to get back to winning ways in this match. The hosts' defending will have to be better than it was in the Welsh capital last week, although perhaps not necessarily at its best given they face a Hull side that has scored just once in their opening two games and that a penalty in last week's win against Norwich. Charlotte Trundley

It is safe to assume Damien Duff is no longer the Fulham player Newcastle fans most love to hate. Duff's disappointing displays during his Tyneside days pale into insignificance next to Darren Bent's double crime of once playing for Sunderland and rejecting the chance to join the hosts this summer. If Bent can expect a hot reception, Newcastle's unsettled Yohan Cabaye may receive a mixed one should he end his one-man strike by returning to action. Louise Taylor

With a combined summer expenditure of over £65m, these teams are hoping to catch the eye this season. Southampton have begun well and are likely again to turn to their record signing Pablo Osvaldo after he came on as a subsitute against Sunderland last week. Having succumbed to 10-man Hull last week, Norwich will be keen to finish the afternoon with a victory. Charlotte Trundley

Mark Hughes has never won at Upton Park as a manager, losing four and drawing one of his five visits, but he knows he needs to improve Stoke's away form. Last week's victory over Crystal Palace showed they remain a formidable proposition at home but they only won twice on their travels last season. It will not be easy against Sam Allardyce's unbeaten West Ham side, however, although the hosts are still without the injured Andy Carroll. Jacob Steinberg

Arsenal dare not lose this one. After the outcry that followed the home defeat to Aston Villa, the wrong result here would lead to meltdowns. Arsène Wenger's team has stabilised with wins over Fenerbahce and Fulham but Tottenham represent a tough proposition. There is form and momentum behind them, fired in no small measure by their lavish summer transfer spend. The loss of Gareth Bale has not brought doom and gloom. It is Arsenal who are desperate for a tonic. David Hytner

On a day the Kop displays a mosaic to mark 100 years since the birth of Bill Shankly, another Scottish manager will look to make an impact at Anfield. David Moyes never won there as Everton manager but, now able to call on Robin van Persie, will fancy his chances more than ever. The hosts are on a good run, however, and in Daniel Sturridge have their own in-form, clinical striker. Sachin Nakrani

It has not exactly been the ideal start to the season for West Bromwich Albion or Swansea. Albion have yet to score, or spend a penny in the transfer market, while Swansea are still searching for their first point after tough opening fixtures against Manchester United and Tottenham. Although Nicolas Anelka is back in the Albion squad after returning from compassionate leave, Ben Foster and Matej Vydra are injured. Wilfried Bony, Ashley Williams and Jonjo Shelvey are all available for Swansea after missing Thursday's Europa League game in Romania. Stuart James

A battling victory over Arsenal on the opening day is all that Paul Lambert's team have to show for their fine start to the season. Narrow defeats by Liverpool and Chelsea are nothing to be ashamed of but Villa need points from games like this if they are to avoid a relegation fight. Of course, the same could be said for Newcastle, who welcome back Yohan Cabaye to the starting lineup. Toby Moses

One month of the season has gone yet with Everton immersed in late transfer sagas and Chelsea involved in the Uefa Super Cup, their campaigns are only just beginning. Samuel Eto'o, Willian, James McCarthy and Gareth Barry could make their debuts for their new teams, though Everton loan signing Romelu Lukaku is ineligible to face his parent club as Roberto Martínez seeks his first league win at Everton. Chelsea were the only team to win at Everton in the league last season and their quality on the counterattack could punish Martínez's side. Andy Hunter

What a difference a year makes. After three games last season West Bromwich Albion were in third place but now they lie bottom with a solitary point and are the only team in the division yet to score. With no Romelu Lukaku or Peter Odemwingie to turn to, Steve Clarke will be hoping that his expensive new recruit Victor Anichebe can produce something against a Fulham side who have also endured a difficult start to the new campaign. Rich Flower

Hull and Cardiff have goalkeeping doubts ahead of their encounter at the KC Stadium. David Marshall sustained a hip injury while with Scotland and Allan McGregor missed the same World Cup qualifiers with a groin problem. The past four matches between these sides have produced 13 goals so Steve Bruce and Malky Mackay will both be hoping to have their first choice No1 available. Rich Flower

Four points from Manchester United's opening three outings is a modest return as David Moyes embarks on a debut season as their manager. A home game against Crystal Palace in the weekend's opening fixture appears a banker to secure victory for only the second time, with United having lost 1-0 at Liverpool in their previous game. But Ian Holloway's side arrive with confidence high having beaten Sunderland 3-1 last time out and Moyes will be without Wayne Rooney as his head injury continues to heal. Jamie Jackson

Manuel Pellegrini is in his early days as Manchester City manager but already there is some pressure on the Chilean following a start to a campaign in which his side lost at Cardiff and scraped to victory over Hull. He will be particularly keen on winning this game, then, as will Mark Hughes given his bitter history with City. Stevan Jovetic could make his first appearance for the visitors. Sachin Nakrani

Mesut Özil may make his Arsenal bow following his £42.5m move from Real Madrid but Sunderland have a midfield debutant of their own. Ki Sung-yueng, a South Korean loaned by Swansea, is earmarked for a key central role as Paolo Di Canio resists the temptation to switch to 4-5-1 against Arsène Wenger's side and instead retains faith with a more adventurous 4-4-2 configuration featuring two wingers in a frequently four-pronged attack. Louise Taylor

Both clubs were busy in the transfer window but while Chris Hughton did most of his business before the season began, Tottenham were forced by circumstance to leave things later. Erik Lamela and Christian Eriksen are expected to start for the hosts following their last-minute arrivals and they could come up against Gary Hooper, who joined Norwich on 26 July but has yet to feature after an injury in pre-season. Rich Flower

West Ham's plans have been thrown into disarray by Andy Carroll's latest setback after the luckless £15m forward suffered a potentially serious foot injury after returning to training this week and it is unknown when he will feature again, forcing Sam Allardyce to sign Mladen Petric on a free transfer. While they wonder where the goals are coming from, Southampton have a wealth of options in attack, although Mauricio Pochettino must find a way of getting the best out of Rickie Lambert and Dani Osvaldo. Jacob Steinberg

With Valencia on Thursday, will Swansea's Europa League adventure prove to be a Premier League distraction? The fans may prefer a long cup run, but the club need only look to Newcastle to see how European ambition can endanger top-flight status. Liverpool have no such distractions, and after sitting out England duty, Daniel Sturridge should be fit as they seek to preserve their 100% record. Toby Moses

José Mourinho's second coming has been a splutter to date, the period of adaptation rather too error-strewn for comfort. The visit of local rivals in Fulham, without a win at Stamford Bridge in 34 years and labouring this term, would normally constitute an opportunity for light relief, but it is hard to predict what Chelsea will muster these days. Four winless matches have raised the stakes already. Martin Jol's side will take encouragement from Basel's midweek success here as they seek to kick-start their own campaign, with their former Chelsea midfielder, Steve Sidwell, having opened talks over a new deal at the club. Dominic Fifield

Liverpool have never topped the Premier League after five matches but victory will deliver their highest points tally at this stage since the competition began in 1992. Creativity could be an issue with Philippe Coutinho injured and Luis Suárez serving the final game of his 10-match ban but in Daniel Sturridge they have a striker out to match John Aldridge's 1987 record of scoring in the first five league matches of a season. Southampton have not won since the opening day but were the last team to beat Liverpool, back in March. Andy Hunter

Crisis what crisis? Alan Pardew is currently doing rather well for someone who was supposed to be a dead man walking. Newcastle have seven points from four games, are playing some pleasing attacking football and could gain further momentum here. As a former Sunderland manager, Hull's Steve Bruce – a boyhood Newcastle fan – can expect a particularly hot reception. Newcastle's Vurnon Anita, currently keeping Cheick Tioté benched, aims to impress once again. Louise Taylor

Paul Lambert returns to the club that he left under a cloud a year ago and while he believes that "the fans have always been good with me", the Aston Villa manager still harbours bitterness towards the Norwich hierachy over his departure. Lambert will be eager to prove his point by getting a good result at Carrow Road but he will have to do so without Jores Okore – Ciaran Clark is expected to step in. Rich Flower

A change of setup may be in order for West Bromwich Albion on Saturday – they are the only side in the division to have started every match in a 4-4-2 formation and it has brought them just two points and one goal so far. Stéphane Sessègnon should bring more creativity and could make a first Albion start against his former club who are propping up the table after a disastrous beginning to the season. Rich Flower

Striker Romelu Lukaku could make his Everton debut. Lukaku was one of the players Sam Allardyce sought to sign for the Hammers during the summer, before a final-day swoop from Roberto Martínez took the Belgian to Merseyside. Both Darron Gibson and Arouna Koné could also feature following knee injuries. Joe Cole, Stewart Downing and Andy Carroll are all out for the Hammers. Jonny Weeks

Having notched their 10th consecutive away win in Marseille, Arsenal return home. Making his Emirates debut, Mesut Özil will again be the star turn, although the potential return of Mikel Arteta from injury is also of note. Stoke, for so long Arsène Wenger's bete noire, arrive in north London in good form and with a growing sense that they are evolving under Mark Hughes. Sachin Nakrani

Tottenham have a number of concerns after their exertions in the Europa League on Thursday night and in addition to definite absentees Étienne Capoue and Aaron Lennon, they could be without Nacer Chadli, Mousa Dembélé, Younes Kaboul and Danny Rose as well. Cardiff will look to take advantage of any weakness shown by the visitors, as they did less than a month ago against Manchester City. Rich Flower

From the Mestalla to Selhurst Park. Thursday night's demolition of Valencia will have Swansea oozing confidence and Palace, having beaten Sunderland in their last home game, need to be ready to exploit any fatigue in what will be City's third match in seven days. The last time the Swans visited, in 2010, defeat left Palace bottom of the Championship. Both have come a long way since. John Ashdown

For the 166th Manchester derby United arrive at the Etihad Stadium with the same tally of points as City. While this indicates stuttering domestic form, Tuesday evening's Champions League group games provided confidence boosts for both teams, with Manuel Pellegrini's side winning 3-0 and David Moyes's 4-2. The Scot can be content with the way Wayne Rooney has started the campaign – three goals and a fresh focus – while his Chilean counterpart will be pleased at how his first-choice strikers, Sergio Agüero and Edin Dzeko, each scored on Tuesday. The cliche states that form is out the window for this occasion so picking a winner is foolish but there is sure to be incident. Jamie Jackson

It will be a tale of two missing strikers in the clash at Villa Park on Saturday afternoon, with Christian Benteke and Sergio Agüero ruled out through injury. Whereas City have Edin Dzeko, Álvaro Negredo and Stevan Jovetic to call upon, Villa will be hoping that their new signing Libor Kozak can repeat his debut heroics from last week at Norwich, where he scored the only goal in a 1-0 victory. Simeon Gholam

Tuesday's victory over Everton in the Capital One Cup relieved some of the pressure on Martin Jol, whose job is said to be in jeopardy following an unconvincing run of form. By coming from behind to win, Fulham showed the bite and balance that critics have accused them of lacking, and the likes of Adel Taarabt, Darren Bent and Dimitar Berbatov moved closer to full fitness. But that was against a weakened Everton side and Fulham will have to raise their performance even higher to prevail against a Cardiff team that have already demonstrated their determination to stay in the top flight. Shahid Khan will be watching closely. Paul Doyle

Not too many would have predicted Hull sitting comfortably in mid-table at any point this season but that is exactly where they are after accruing seven points from their first five games. West Ham have struggled somewhat for goals so far, but have coped well defensively, particularly away from home where both of their games so far have ended goalless. An edgy game with few goalscoring opportunities at either end would not be too much of a surprise. Simeon Gholam

While Manchester United still smart from the 4-1 derby humiliation at Manchester City, the midweek Capital One Cup defeat of Liverpool offered considerable succour before West Bromwich Albion's arrival at Old Trafford. If David Moyes is serious about retaining the title for the club then this is precisely the ilk of opposition who must be beaten. Last time out the fixture was a helter-skelter 5-5 draw in Sir Alex Ferguson's last game as manager. Moyes would settle for as 1-0 win, Steve Clarke for any kind of draw. Jamie Jackson

Southampton's win at Liverpool last Saturday was an unexpected but welcome bonus; now for the seemingly routine task of the visit of Crystal Palace. Yet the home side should not take victory over Ian Holloway's team, depleted by injuries, for granted given that their first two matches at St Mary's have seen them draw with Sunderland and West Ham. Mauricio Pochettino could do with £14.6m striker Daniel Osvaldo breaking his duck. Jacob Steinberg

A game for the purist. Michael Laudrup's easy-on-the-eye Swansea City side take on an Arsenal team full of confidence on the back of a run of eight straight wins in all competitions, including Wednesday's penalty shootout victory over West Bromwich Albion in the Capital One Cup. With a long list of injuries, Arsène Wenger will be desperately hoping that Aaron Ramsey and Mathieu Flamini pass fitness tests. Swansea, who have failed to win at home in their past seven Premier League matches, are likely to be without their captain, Ashley Williams, who is struggling with an ankle problem. Stuart James

This game would be intriguing enough without José Mourinho and André Villas-Boas coming up against each other for the first time since a once close relationship fractured. The north London derby aside, this campaign to date has been a real show of strength from Tottenham, a miserly defence and powerful midfield bullying opponents into submission. Chelsea will be braced for another stern test and, with Juan Mata back in contention, will still hope Ramires passes a late fitness test. Dominic Fifield

These sides enjoyed midweek Capital One Cup wins against lower-league opposition and although Stephen Ireland went off injured having scored for Stoke against Tranmere – his first goal in almost two years – he is expected to return in time for Sunday's match. Gary Hooper found the net twice for Norwich against Watford and may now make his first Premier League start for the visitors. Jonny Weeks

Luis Suárez's first Premier League game since his biting ban; Simon Mignolet's return to Wearside; Sunderland caretaker manager Kevin Ball's big audition for the vacancy as Paolo Di Canio's successor. There are sub-plots galore but do not be surprised if Lee Cattermole attempts to provoke Suárez as the home side – without their key striker, Steven Fletcher – seek to improve on a woeful tally of one point in five games. They could probably do without Mignolet reminding them of his goalkeeping brilliance. Louise Taylor

Having secured victory over West Ham last week with two stunning Leighton Baines free-kicks, Everton remain the only team in the Premier League yet to be beaten. From the poignant Hillsborough tribute before kick-off to Demba Ba's dramatic last-gasp equaliser, this fixture was one of last season's unforgettable games. Now, with Roberto Martínez attempting to adapt Everton's style of play attractively and with Newcastle having the joint second leakiest defence in this season's Premier League, an entertaining affair should be on the cards. Simeon Gholam

After a pair of 3-2 defeats, Newcastle will be grateful for any sort of good news, and that might come with Yohan Cabaye returning to the starting lineup. The French midfielder came on in the loss at Everton, and Alan Pardew thinks he could feature from the start on Saturday. The Cardiff manager, Malky Mackay, has no further injury concerns, with summer signing Andreas Cornelius still working his way back to fitness. Nick Miller

Mark Hughes returns to the club that he left under something of a cloud in the summer of 2011 having admitted he made a mistake in going from Fulham to "further his career"– a decision that saw him presiding over a chaotic 10-month period at QPR. Hughes seems to have found some stability now at Stoke while Fulham have problems of their own with Martin Jol's managership starting to sink as the home fans turn against him. Rich Flower

Both sides will have a spring in their step as each seek a third consecutive win. Hull have been confident and purposeful at home so far, although the absence of their incisive midfielder Robbie Brady is a blow. Villa are also missing a key man in Christian Benteke, but last week's win over Manchester City demonstrated their resilience and tenacity, which they will need to show again here. Tom Davies

This would appear to be one of the day's more obvious home bankers. Luis Suárez's winning and scoring return at Sunderland, and his link-up play with Daniel Sturridge, promise to give Liverpool's attack extra potency. Palace have not been overwhelmed by anyone so far but are struggling to score, beset by injuries and their search for a first away point is likely to continue. Tom Davies

Manuel Pellegrini has problems due to Joe Hart's awful form and the need to rebuild belief following the 3-1 hiding Bayern Munich handed his side in the midweek Champions League game. Everton, the league's only unbeaten side, arrive with two more points, and are a tricky proposition due to the form of Romelu Lukaku and Ross Barkley. Given Alvaro Negredo's consistent impact whenever he is given a chance, the Spanish striker could start in place of Edin Dzeko for City. Jamie Jackson

A win against the champions would be a big tick on Kevin Ball's CV as the Sunderland board take the international break to appoint a replacement for Paolo Di Canio. The home side are still missing Steven Fletcher and need Jozy Altidore to start repaying the £8m spent on the American striker. Meanwhile, David Moyes needs all three points to stem the United in crisis narrative. Toby Moses

Chris Hughton will want his Norwich side to recoup at least a point on Sunday or the momentum of last week's 1-0 victory at Stoke could go to waste, particularly with the daunting prospect of a trip to Arsenal looming after the international break. Chelsea have not lost at Carrow Road since December 1994, but in the absence of Fernando Torres, scoring enough goals to secure a win could be problematic. Rich Flower

This is a meeting between two of the Premier League's dark horses, with both sides justifiably upbeat about their prospects this season. Southampton were briefly as high as fourth last weekend but the visit of Michael Laudrup's side promises to be a stern test. The games are coming thick and fast for Swansea, and Southampton will hope that their Europa League exertions on Thursday will have a negative effect on the Welsh side. Jacob Steinberg

It is to be hoped that the headlines are driven by what happens on the field, rather than off it where it is to be expected that Tottenham's fans will sing what they want, which will not sit well with the police. The potential for conflict bubbles between these rivals yet Tottenham simply intend to extend their solid start. Only Olivier Giroud and John Terry have scored against them in 11 games so far. West Ham need a tonic after a poor spell. David Hytner

Talk of crisis was washed away by the wave of goodwill that arrived with Mesut Özil and Arsenal are looking for their 11th win in a row in all competitions. Bacary Sagna has a hamstring injury while Santi Cazorla is not yet fit, meaning another team light on width. Albion are basking in their win at Old Trafford but Scott Sinclair's hamstring strain picked up there will keep him out, though Nicolas Anelka and Chris Brunt could return. Nick Miller

Norwich travel to the league leaders with just one win in their past four games and finding themselves in the relegation zone. A trip, then, to the Emirates to face a side brimming with confidence is not what Chris Hughton would want right now. Aaron Ramsey kept up his impressive recent form with a goal for Wales in midweek and will pose a threat again. John Stephens

Cardiff City might consider the wounds suffered over recent weeks to have been self-inflicted, the departure of Iain Moody as chief scout unsettling Malky Mackay when he should have been savouring a promising start to his side's top-flight return. Chelsea have not lost at home to the Welsh club since 1981, yet José Mourinho still expects an awkward challenge. "They are motivated, they beat Manchester City, have already won away from home, and the boys who have come back from Chile and Iceland will be full of good feelings," he said. "Losing the scout is a problem for the owner, for Mackay, not the players". Dominic Fifield

Only one point seperates promoted Hull from opponents with a long-established top-flight status, yet few expect Steve Bruce's side to get much out of their visit to Goodison Park. Everton have lost just once this season, have generally looked impressive, and in Leighton Baines and Romelu Lukaku have two players who are shining at international and club level right now. John Stephens

Few would have predicted Southampton would find themselves above the champions after seven games of the season. Mauricio Pochettino's side have prospered thanks to a solid defence and from securing key victories, such as their 1-0 triumph against Liverpool. United won at Sunderland in their last outing with a double from Adnan Januzaj and he is likely to feature again. John Stephens

The last thing Alan Pardew would have wanted before Newcastle face Daniel Sturridge and Luis Suárez is a centre-back injury crisis but that is what he has got. Fabricio Coloccini and Steven Taylor are absent for the visit of what Brendan Rodgers has described as the best strike partnership in England. Victory for Liverpool would take them top for a couple of hours at least. Sachin Nakrani

Stoke have lost their last three games and are no doubt hoping to recapture the home form they have been noted for. Four goals in seven games have left Mark Hughes's men with the worst goals-scored record in the division, and they face a West Bromwich side who are on an encouraging unbeaten run. In Saido Berahino, Albion also possess an exciting, young goal-threat. John Stephens

Gus Poyet will have his first taste of Premier League management against a side yet to win at home in the league this season. Michael Laudrup will hope that Michu can excel against the bottom-placed team although the Dane will also be wary of the return to Sunderland's ranks of Steven Fletcher, who should lead the visitors' attack after recovering from a shoulder injury. John Stephens

While Manuel Pellegrini's attacking instincts have seen Manchester City take teams apart at home, it has been a different and more worrying story on the road. Leads have been squandered and the return of a solitary point is hardly the stuff of champions-in-waiting. Are City too open? They will encounter a West Ham team that would love to suck them in and punch on the counter. Cat and mouse beckons. David Hytner

Spurs have beaten Villa 4-0 on their own patch twice in the past 10 months but this latest contest promises to be closer. Christian Benteke, a transfer target for Spurs in the summer, has a chance of returning to a Villa side that defeated Manchester City in their last home league game. The spotlight will again shine brightly on Andros Townsend, the winger who made such an impressive contribution for England against Montenegro and Poland. Stuart James

Ian Holloway has described the visit of Fulham as a "must not lose game" for Crystal Palace yet privately the manager must accept this derby provides his team with a great chance to capture just their second win of the season. Selhurst Park should be rocking under the lights and Fulham, who may include Maarten Stekelenburg in their side, could well be there for the taking. Sachin Nakrani

The probable return of Christian Benteke to the Aston Villa starting line-up adds a new dimension to a fixture between two sides with grand ambitions. Villa, who have already beaten Arsenal and Manchester City this campaign, will hope that the recovery of their leading striker will herald a return to winning ways against an Everton side who have lost only once in the Premier League this season. Joe Sykes

Keith Millen's first game in charge of Crystal Palace could scarcely be more daunting. Arsenal, despite losing to Borussia Dortmund in midweek, come into this fixture with a feeling in north London that they have not had it this good since the halcyon days of Dennis Bergkamp and Thierry Henry.The visitor's midfield alone has twelve goals between them in the Premier League while Palace's has managed just one. After Saturday, Millen, or whoever replaces him, might have a better idea of what he has let himself in for. Joe Sykes

Brendan Rodgers' Liverpool will be looking for revenge after last season's double by Steve Clarke's side, with Luis Suárez and Daniel Sturridge in form with 10 goals between them in the league. Albion have a good recent record at Anfield, winning on their last two visits, and are unbeaten away this season in the top flight, while Liverpool have already been beaten at home by Southampton. Hassanin Mubarak

Mark Hughes returns to Manchester with his side having managed only one victory in their past six Premier League games, but this could be the best opportunity for Stoke to register their first victory at United for 37 years. United have won the last 10 home meetings between the two sides, but have managed only one victory in their last four matches this season at Old Trafford. Hassanin Mubarak

Both clubs left London licking their wounds after 4-1 defeats at Arsenal and Chelsea respectively last Saturday, results which have left them sitting either side of the relegation line. Lack of goals is the issue for both, and Norwich hope to welcome back Ricky van Wolfswinkel and Johan Elmander, while for the visitors Craig Bellamy could return at the club where he started his career. Paul Chronnell

All the talk this week has been about Pajtim Kasami and his homage to Marco van Basten but, while Fulham have stolen the limelight, the most impressive recent performance was Southampton's point at Old Trafford. Mauricio Pochettino's side have three wins in their last four games and they will be confident that their blend of steely defence and high-octane pressing can sustain their momentum. Joe Sykes

This meeting provides a proper test for both sides, the onus on Chelsea to prove they need not just rely on the counterattack against elite opposition, and on Manchester City to emerge victorious from a visit to a title rival. José Mourinho can see similarities with City now to his Chelsea back in 2004, when lavish financial investment demanded a coherent championship challenge. This game should provide an early gauge to these clubs' aspirations this season. Dominic Fifield

Gus Poyet's first home game in charge of Sunderland. Alan Pardew's chance to avenge last April's 3-0 defeat at St James' Park. Lee Cattermole versus Cheik Tioté in central midfield. Steven Taylor marking Steven Fletcher. Wes Brown's potential comeback. Sunderland desperate to increase their return of one point from eight games. Pardew acutely aware defeat would play badly with Mike Ashley, Newcastle's owner. One of the most partisan atmospheres anyone will encounter at a football ground anywhere. Subplots galore. Louise Taylor

West Ham side go to the Liberty Stadium with only eight points so far this season but will be buoyed by their recent visit to White Hart Lane, where the spotlight fell firmly on Ravel Morrison. Michael Laudrup's side won comfortably in this fixture last season and will hope to grab their fourth home victory of the campaign, while the visitors will be looking for a first triumph at Swansea in 30 years. Hassanin Mubarak

Tottenham came through their toughest Europa League test to date at Sheriff on Thursday to strengthen not only their status as favourites for the competition but the feeling that their style is perfect for away assignments. It is at home where the formula can elude them and it has done in the previous matches with Chelsea and West Ham. They know that they are expected to beat Steve Bruce's injury-hit Hull side, who will feature Tom Huddlestone playing against his former club for the first time. David Hytner

Everyone is a critic in Arsène Wenger's eyes, even when Arsenal are top of the league and the current barb is that the position is false as they have not played anyone decent, apart from Tottenham at home. Moreover, they have lost to Borussia Dortmund and Chelsea, who definitely are decent. "It's down to us to prove people wrong," Wenger said, a little wearily. Liverpool, for whom Luis Suárez and Daniel Sturridge are flying, are also decent and it will be revealing to see how Arsenal fare. David Hytner

Martin Jol insists he is not feeling the pressure as Fulham supporters grumble about their team's shoddy form. But he must know that a repeat of last week's abject display at Southampton could lead to a severe beating at the hands of Manchester United. The visitors may not have found their groove yet this season, either, but an away win still seems the most likely outcome. Paul Doyle

Having secured their first win of the season in last Sunday's Wear-Tyne derby, Sunderland head to the KC Stadium in buoyant mood, but Gus Poyet's side would be wise to travel with caution. Hull impressed in their previous two matches, both against Spurs, and in Steve Bruce have a manager who will be determined to get one over the club that sacked him close to two years ago. Sachin Nakrani

The headline news is the dropping of Joe Hart as the goalkeeper is finally axed for what has been a year-long run of howlers. Beyond this, though, Manchester City must return to winning ways after the loss at Chelsea as Manuel Pellegrini seeks to bridge the gap to the leaders Arsenal. With Vincent Kompany an injury concern, with his current thigh problem meaning he may not be available until after the international break, and with Costel Pantilimon making his Premier League debut, Norwich City may just fancy their chances of grabbing a result. Jamie Jackson

Chelsea are not the team Alan Pardew would have wanted the weekend after losing at Sunderland. With Newcastle having won only one league game at home this season, and Chelsea on a hot streak, this promises to be a tough afternoon for Pardew's talented but inconsistent team. It hardly helps the Geordie cause that injuries dictate Fabricio Coloccini and Steven Taylor, Newcastle's best central-defensive pair, are unavailable to try to halt the Fernando Torres renaissance. Louise Taylor

It feels like a long time ago since people were complimenting Stoke for making a positive start to the season. Mark Hughes's side have lost four of their last five games and find themselves outside the relegation zone on goal-difference alone. Not the time, then, to be facing high-flying Southampton, although the visitors could be without record-signing Pablo Osvaldo due to injury. Sachin Nakrani

The Crystal Palace caretaker manager, Keith Millen, takes his bottom-place side to The Hawthorns, a venue where they have a decent record. The last time West Bromwich Albion won at home against Palace was nine years ago, but with the visitors losing eight from nine games this season, and managing no points away from home so far, this looks like another loss for the London club. Hassanin Mubarak

West Ham have not won at home in the league since beating Cardiff City on the opening day and after three straight defeats at Upton Park, Sam Allardyce will view this match as a chance to move away from the bottom three. The manager's main decision is whether to stick with his strikerless formation or to start with Carlton Cole, who have not scored in their past three games. Jacob Steinberg

The first-ever top-flight encounter between these two old foes will take place amid the kind of security usually reserved for presidential visits. Let's hope Mike Dean takes care, bearing in mind the last time he refereed this fixture a coin struck him on the head. Neither team is in great form and Swansea can be encouraged that Cardiff have faced more shots than any other team in the Premier League so far this season. The home side do, however, have Craig Bellamy back, the match-winner when the sides last met in 2011. Daniel Taylor

There have been few complaints on the road this season from André Villas-Boas and Tottenham head to Goodison Park seeking a fourth win in five league trips away from White Hart Lane. Wednesday's exertions in the Capital One Cup should not hinder a squad with their depth, either. Everton, however, are unbeaten at home in the league this calender year and will go above Spurs with a fourth successive league win at Goodison. The all-Belgian duel between Romelu Lukaku and Jan Vertonghen may be key. Andy Hunter

Fresh from their derby win over Swansea, Cardiff could be forgiven for thinking this is a good time to be travelling to Aston Villa, who have picked up only three points out of 15 at home this season, failed to score in 375 minutes and go into this fixture with injuries to key players, including Gabriel Agbonlahor and Andreas Weimann. Christian Benteke will be hoping to end a run of four games without a goal against a Cardiff team that are two places above Villa. Stuart James

After last weekend's lurch into complacency – as well as a fine Newcastle performance – came a midweek reminder for Chelsea of the rewards hard graft can deliver. They will be eager now to restore momentum to their Premier League campaign at Stamford Bridge. The Londoners can move back to within two points of the top with a win and, with Samuel Eto'o and Demba Ba scorers again against Schalke, will tear into West Bromwich Albion and their former Chelsea coach, Steve Clarke, with relish. The Baggies, so often the slayers of Chelsea managers up at The Hawthorns, may have won already at Old Trafford this season but they face an awkward afternoon . Dominic Fifield

Everton will be licking their lips in anticipation of facing a team who have lost their past seven games and not scored for 263 minutes. This is likely to be Keith Millen's last game in temporary charge with Aitor Karanka set for talks on Monday. Roberto Martínez, meanwhile, has told James McCarthy to play his natural game despite the risk of missing the Merseyside derby if he is booked. Marcus Christenson

An impending international break plus a trip to Anfield, where Fulham have won once in 32 visits in all competitions, presents an ominous brew for Martin Jol as he battles to convince new owner Shahid Khan he can take the club forward. Fulham were beaten 4-0 and 3-1 last season by Brendan Rodgers's team, who will be confident of an immediate response to defeat at Arsenal last weekend. Liverpool have scored 12 goals in five league games since Luis Suárez returned from suspension, with the Uruguayan and Daniel Sturridge grabbing 10 of them. Andy Hunter

West Ham have scored only eight league goals all season, just one more than Norwich conceded in 90 awful minutes at Manchester City last week. Chris Hughton's side would certainly not have gone to the Etihad Stadium expecting to win – they may not even have thought they could escape with a draw – but the manner of their capitulation surely leaves the manager's position hanging by a thread. Rich Flower

Hull have accumulated 14 points from their first 10 games, mainly through the virtue of being well organised with a solid defence. Scoring goals has not been as easy and will get even harder now that Sone Aluko has torn an achilles. Now would be a fine time for Danny Graham, back after being ineligible to face parent club Sunderland last week, to score his first league goal since 1 January. Rich Flower

The champions against the leaders can be billed as the game of the season so far, as Manchester United hope to pull off what Liverpool and Borussia Dortmund were unable to manage in Arsenal's previous two outings and beat the Gunners. The chat has been of how Arsène Wenger's band may arrive at Old Trafford as favourites for the first time in memory, but with United having the crowd behind them and their undoubted pedigree this could go either way, though due to Arsenal's eight-point advantage a draw would suit them better. Jamie Jackson

Two South American managers. Adam Johnson with a point to prove against his former City employers. City anxious to atone for three successive Premier League defeats – all 1-0 – against Sunderland at the Stadium of Light. Manuel Pellegrini craving a title, Gus Poyet desperate . Two managers with genuine goalkeeping dilemmas. Sunderland's And Wes Brown fit again for the first time in almost two years and back alongside his former Manchester United team-mate John O'Shea in central defence. Louise Taylor

Both these sides have struggled of late, with Swansea capping their recent unconvincing streak on Thursday by conceding a 90th-minute equaliser for the second Europa League game in a row. Stoke, with two points from their past six Premier League games and goalkeeper Asmir Begovic as joint-top scorer, are in danger of matching Crystal Palace as the division's most out-of-form side. Rich Flower

André Villas-Boas says he expects Newcastle to play; what he did not say was that he prays they do. He has become frustrated at how visiting teams have massed men behind the ball and his side have struggled to break them down. He continues to search for answers and he is keen for Tottenham to improve upon their scoring record: they have , nine in 10 league matches, three of them penalties. Newcastle are pepped by their win over Chelsea but they remain wildly unpredictable. David Hytner

Southampton lost this fixture 6-1 last season and they have not won at Arsenal in 26 years. But it will be a different Southampton that takes to the field, one flying after the club's finest start to a top-flight season and pepped by England call-ups and all-round acclaim. Unbeaten in eight, the best streak in the division, they have got results at Liverpool and Manchester United. Can they withstand an Arsenal team looking to bounce back from their defeat at Old Trafford? David Hytner

Only Colin Harvey and Joe Royle won their first Merseyside derbies as Everton manager and Roberto Martínez's team must improve significantly on recent displays for the Spaniard to join that company. Everton disappointed against Crystal Palace and Tottenham Hotspur, lacking inspiration from either Romelu Lukaku or Kevin Mirallas, but are unbeaten at Goodison Park in 2013. Liverpool are 11 points better off than at the same stage of last season – Everton have the same points total as they did this time last year – and Brendan Rodgers will hope there is no international toll on Luis Suárez, Daniel Sturridge and Steven Gerrard as he seeks a first win over the Goodison Park club. Andy Hunter

For now, Fulham have chosen to reinforce Martin Jol rather than replace him. This is the first match since René Meulensteen was appointed as head coach to help the manager and it will be interesting to see whether, between them, the Dutchmen can find a way of making an alarmingly fragile Fulham more solid. If they can, the side has enough attacking quality to climb out of the relegation zone. But the improvement will have to be instantaneous to avoid defeat against slick Swansea. Paul Doyle

Hull are one of only five teams unbeaten at home this season and welcome a Palace side who have so far failed to register a point on their travels. This is likely to be Keith Millen's last game in temporary charge with Tony Pulis expected to be appointed in the next few days. Meanwhile, Hull will be boosted by the news that Robert Koren and Robbie Brady are fit after injury. Niall McCague

There will be a deservedly warm welcome for Chris Hughton, the Norwich manager sacked almost three years ago by Newcastle, but disappointment should Alan Pardew's side fail to record a third straight league win. Victories against Chelsea and Spurs have raised the Tyneside bar and Pardew trusts his contingent of France players will be inspired by their country's last ditch World Cup qualification. Hatem Ben Arfa, a wonderful Hughton signing, is desperate to play in Brazil but may well find himself on the bench again on Saturday. Louise Taylor

Both sides have struggled of late, Sunderland sitting three points off the bottom and Stoke winless from their last eight league games. The 1-0 win against Manchester City will have surely restored some confidence to a depleted Sunderland, who can move out of the relegation zone with victory on Saturday. Glenn Whelan should return to the Stoke squad after his hamstring injury. Niall McCague

How Sam Allardyce must be craving a fit, battering ram of a striker who could unsettle a Chelsea team whose away form to date this term – five points from a possible 15 – renders them vulnerable. An Andy Carroll, perhaps. The hosts may have Carlton Cole as an alternative, but the visitors will be ready to confront a packed midfield as they search of a derby victory to pep up their title challenge. "We have to do better away from home,"admitted José Mourinho. "But we have had difficult matches away so far." This derby may well prove to be another. Dominic Fifield

This will be the first time these two clubs have met since March 1975, when Ryan Giggs was 16 months old. Giggs will return to the city of his birth for this game and, with Michael Carrick and Phil Jones sidelined through injury, the Welshman has a chance of starting in central midfield. United may be without Nemanja Vidic but are looking for a fourth straight league win, and as Manchester City found out, Cardiff are no pushovers at home. Stuart James

For City (eighth) and Spurs (seventh) now is the time for a surge up the table as the congested winter programme starts. Manuel Pellegrini, still without Vincent Kompany and David Silva, hopes City's supreme home form – 15 points from five games – continues, while his opposite number, André Villas-Boas, needs Spurs' travelling goals record of nine from six outings to improve. Jamie Jackson

Albion have finished comfortably above Villa in each of the past two campaigns, which is something that would once have been unthinkable, although it looks like it will be much tighter this season. Only goal difference separates these West Midlands rivals, who sit mid-table after a decidedly mixed set of results across the first three months. The international break came at a good time for Villa, who welcome back Andreas Weimann, Gabriel Agbonlahor, Antonio Luna and Fabian Delph. For Albion, Nicolas Anelka and Scott Sinclair return. Stuart James

Unbeaten in three matches or with only one win in six? Villa fans view the club's season so far in different ways, some believing progress is being made under Paul Lambert and others maintaining that there has been no improvement since last term's narrow escape. Losing at home to the bottom-placed team would give ammunition to the naysayers while a victory would ensconce them safely in mid-table and allay any fears for a while, especially if Christian Benteke regains his scoring form. No such ambiguity at Sunderland: their season has been wretched but Gus Poyet will see this as a game that can be won. Paul Doyle

The Premier League leaders will travel to the Welsh capital hoping to pick up a better result than the two Manchester clubs managed. City were beaten 3-2 by Cardiff back in August and United were held to a 2-2 draw last Sunday. On both occasions Cardiff scored from set pieces. Arsène Wenger, who praised Cardiff for their "solidarity, togetherness and fantastic support", has Kieran Gibbs available again after the left-back missed Tuesday's Champions League win over Marseille through illness. Stuart James

Fresh from the splendid Merseyside derby, Everton will be confident of maintaining their unbeaten home record against a Stoke side who secured their first victory in nine last weekend. Romelu Lukaku continues to demonstrate all the forward qualities Chelsea currently lack and a win for Everton could elevate them briefly into the top four. Stoke have not won away since August but a rejuvenated Charlie Adam could be one to watch after his goal against Sunderland. Louis Richards

Any fears of a crisis on Tyneside have been banished following a run of three successive victories that has moved the side up to a comfortable eighth. Loïc Rémy has scored in all three games to take his total to eight for the season, which has helped to distract fans from the ominous spectre of Joe Kinnear (sort of). Steve Clarke, meanwhile, has quietly guided Albion to mid-table and they have lost just once away from The Hawthorns. Louis Richards

Tony Pulis begins his Crystal Palace career with the proverbial six-pointer. These sides have managed just five wins between them this season amid a series of substandard performances to make them both strong relegation candidates. Palace's victory at Hull last weekend was their first away win of the campaign and Pulis will want to maintain some momentum ahead of their consecutive home games against West Ham and Cardiff. Norwich will be hoping Leroy Fer can continue his recent goalscoring prowess. Louis Richards

Both managers enter this fixture knowing that a bad result could quickly propel their names to the front of the sack race. Without a win in five games, Sam Allardyce's side are clearly suffering from the lack of a quality striker and after one goal in four games, Carlton Cole may merit a start. For Fulham Darren Bent and Dimitar Berbatov may have 195 Premier League goals between them, but their partnership continues to show few indications of prospering. Louis Richards

Southampton have won only once at Stamford Bridge since 1995 and yet, aware of Chelsea's current inconsistencies, Mauricio Pochettino's side will travel to the capital with confidence. This is the latest stern test in a tricky run of fixtures – they must play Manchester City and Spurs before Christmas – which will put their current placing of fifth in proper context. Their hosts were excellent at West Ham last weekend and awful in the midweek defeat at Basel. José Mourinho will consider changes to his team, with Fernando Torres likely to start up front and Juan Mata pushing for inclusion. Dominic Fifield

Hull are the fifth club Steve Bruce has managed against Liverpool and he has a decent record with the previous four – losing only five of 17 encounters – but he enters the 18th meeting with a serious lack of firepower. While Brendan Rodgers can boast a striker with 21 goals in his last 22 league games, Luis Suárez, Hull have scored just four league goals at home all season, the lowest in the division with Crystal Palace, and their only win in the last seven matches was courtesy of a Carlos Cuéllar own goal against Sunderland. Liverpool have never lost to Hull in 16 fixtures. Andy Hunter

4-0, 4-1, 5-0, 7-0, 5-2, 6-0, 4-2: scores registered by Manchester City on their own turf this season to chill Michael Laudrup's Swansea City as they arrive at the Etihad Stadium. Or maybe not: the urbane Dane already has a trophy – last season's Capital One Cup – and a burgeoning reputation as the brightest of managerial talents whose team play the carpet-football admired by aficionados. If he can successfully plot to claim even one point to halt City's so far perfect record of five league wins before their own crowd then Laudrup will add a further feather to his cap. Jamie Jackson

Tottenham's supporters could be forgiven for feeling a sense of foreboding bearing in mind the harrowing defeat at Manchester City and the fact they have not beaten Manchester United on their own ground since 2001. United put in their best performance of the David Moyes era against Bayer Leverkusen in midweek. Spurs also won, but Europa League 2-0 victories against Tromso only go so far when the manager is under pressure. The question for André Villas-Boas is whether his team have got the 6-0 pummelling against City out of their system. A win would certainly go a long way towards strengthening his own position. Daniel Taylor

Though Tony Pulis's Crystal Palace are still three points and an 11-goal swing from safety, victory over 15th-placed Cardiff City would add to their growing momentum. They have taken seven points from a possible 12 in recent weeks (three from six since Pulis arrived) and have no new injuries following their 1-0 midweek defeat of West Ham. Cardiff could field Craig Bellamy, who has recovered from a hamstring injury, as they hunt a first goal on the road since mid-October. Jonny Weeks

For West Ham this might have to be a simple Operation Luis Suárez job after the striker's astonishing midweek display against Norwich. The visitors are probably not expecting that much of themselves with their last victory at Anfield over 50 years ago in September 1963. Liverpool will be strong favourites having won their last four league games at home and scoring 16 times in the process. Jimmy Norval

There should be only one instruction David Moyes gives his Manchester United side before facing Newcastle United: win. After Wednesday evening's 1-0 reverse to Everton at Old Trafford the manager – and his side – dare not drop further points in front of their own crowd, with 12 the margin to the leaders Arsenal, going into the weekend. It is the same gap to the relegation zone and with United also five points from a Champions League berth a further defeat would mean "crisis" would not be an inflated term to describe where the champions would find themselves as they embark on the jam-packed festive programme. Jamie Jackson

A 3-1 defeat here last season was one of the low points of Roberto Mancini's reign as City turned in a listless and error-strewn performance en route to a 3-1 defeat. Another Southampton win is hardly out of the question the strains of their early-season exertions are starting to take a toll on Mauricio Pochettino's squad, as injuries mount. City's midweek victory over West Bromwich Albion suggests they are beginning to achieve greater parity between their home and away form. Paul Doyle

With Arsenal not playing until Sunday this match offers Chelsea the chance to move within a point of top spot, with recent form suggesting they will do just that. José Mourinho's men have won their last three league fixtures, scoring 10 times in the process. In contrast Stoke are struggling, with Wednesday's goalless draw with Cardiff proving a missed opportunity to record only a second top-flight victory since late August. Jonathan Walters scored two own goals and missed a penalty when these sides met at the Britannia Stadium last season — a repeat is almost unthinkable. Sachin Nakrani

André Villas-Boas's team still sit three points off fourth spot despite the recent calamity at Manchester City. They have since gathered momentum by beating Fulham and gaining a point against Manchester United but Sunderland can spring surprises at home, as Manchester City and Newcastle can testify. This 111th meeting between the two sides should be a close one. Jimmy Norval

After Luis Suárez's four-goal festival at Anfield made it 22 goals shipped in their last five away games, Norwich would have rather had a home fixture. Chris Hughton will be hoping his side can replicate the performance that saw them beat West Brom 4-0 in May. The home side have not won in their last four league games so will be looking for three points on Saturday. Jimmy Norval

For Arsenal, the big tests have come and have been passed, apart from the visit to Old Trafford, but the coming fortnight or so will provide the definitive proof as to whether they are likely to be good enough to win the title. After Everton, come Manchester City (away) and Chelsea (home). Arsène Wenger is not looking beyond Everton, who are flying after their victory at United and who have lost fewer games than any other Premier League side. David Hytner

Against Aston Villa, Fulham need rewards to accompany a re-energised display. They would do well to be wary of their visitors, impressive victors at St Mary's on Wednesday where they bit three times on the counterattack to jettison Southampton's unbeaten home record. Gabriel Agbonlahor's pace on the break will threaten the hosts, With Villa's confidence growing, this could be awkward. Dominic Fifield

With no wins during their last five away games in the Premier League and just one win in more than 13 years when travelling to this part of South Wales, history and form suggest Steve Bruce's team will struggle. Having said that, Hull have impressed this season and lie only a single point behind the Swans, who are looking for some consistency having lost two, won two and drawn two of their last six games. Jimmy Norval

Without a win in their last five Premier League fixtures, Cardiff find themselves hovering dangerously close to the relegation zone with only a point separating them from the bottom three, but this is the first of three home games in four and they are looking to make that sequence pay. West Bromwich are themselves only a point and a place above Cardiff having lost three games in a row. Callum Hosier

Crystal Palace's revival faces the acid test. Ten points from the past five matches and only one goal conceded have fired their survival chances. Tony Pulis, the new manager, is a natural-born fighter but if José Mourinho is sure of what to expect from his counterpart – "maybe a style that people are not attracted by" – he also knows precisely what he expects of his Chelsea team: "We lost the last game to Stoke. We need a victory." David Hytner

Fulham represent a test of Everton's mind-set as much as their quality. The London club have never won a league game at Goodison Park, where Everton return following a fine week on the road. The home side can ill-afford to show complacency against a side that recorded its first win under the new manager Rene Meulensteen last week, and must do so without James McCarthy. Andy Hunter

Mark Hughes takes Stoke to Hull, as 12th hosts 13th at the KC. Buoyant in the wake of their recent 3-2 win over Chelsea, Hughes will hope to arrest the poor away form which has seen Stoke lose four of their last five on their travels. Hull have conceded three goals at home all season, and given their emphatic win over Liverpool a fortnight ago, their home form will be the bedrock of the campaign. James Dutton

The day's early match sees Manchester City, buoyed by their midweek win at Bayern Munich, looking to turn over the Premier League leaders. If either of these teams can claim victory they will lay down the clearest marker yet of where the championship might end up in May. And, as both managers send their teams out to play high-tempo stuff, this should definitely be an exciting contest. Jamie Jackson

More than three years after Alan Pardew's sacking by Southampton, the memory still rankles. "On a personal level this is a game I really want to win," he said. "Losing my job was an injustice. But I'm looking forward to seeing my old players like Rickie Lambert and Adam Lallana, who've done absolutely brilliantly." Newcastle's underrated Vurnon Anita has a chance to impress in place of the suspended Yohan Cabaye. Louise Taylor

Only goal difference is keeping West Ham out of the relegation zone, with four defeats in the last five games dragging the Hammers down to 17th. Sunderland threatened a brief revival under Gus Poyet with their 1-0 win over Manchester City last month but now find themselves five points adrift at the foot of the table, having lost three of their last four. The home side have won just twice at home this season butwill fancy their chances against the division's worst travellers. James Dutton

The last time these two teams met at Villa Park it took a late header from Javier Hernández to seal a win for Manchester Utd. David Moyes would certainly take something similar as he looks to arrest a run of two consecutive league defeats. The Scot is without the injured Robin van Persie, however, ahead of facing an Aston Villa side who have won only one of their last four games. Callum Hosier

Swansea will be psyched up after a tiring round-trip to St Gallen in Switzerland, where they lost but still moved into the knockout phase of the Europa League. Standing in their way will be a side who picked themselves up from a 5-1 loss at Liverpool with a 2-0 win at West Brom, where Gary Hooper scored for the fifth time this season. Every time he has scored Norwich won the game. Callum Hosier

Only three points separate Tottenham from Liverpool as second travel to sixth. Spurs have been frugal at home this season, with only Aston Villa scoring fewer goals in front of their own fans, but consecutive away wins have healed the wound of their calamitous loss at Manchester City. Liverpool have not won away from home since September, and are looking to end a hoodoo that has seen them lose their last five games at White Hart Lane. James Dutton

Tony Pulis goes in search of a third consecutive home victory, one which could lift Crystal Palace out of the relegation zone. Marouane Chamakh will be looking to score in his fourth successive game and against a Newcastle United side who have lost just one of their last seven matches, with victories over Chelsea, Tottenham Hotspur and at Manchester United coming in that spell. James Dutton

The belief appears wide spread: Manchester City will win the title if they can find some form on their travels. Imperious at home, they have shown their skittishness at places like Cardiff, Stoke and Sunderland. They will expect to beat Fulham and it would be a statement to follow those made at Bayern Munich and at home to Arsenal, but they have enjoyed the initial upsurge in performance that tends to come from replacing the manager. Rene Meulensteen, though, faces a long road ahead. David Hytner

Shifting the spotlight from Luis Suárez takes some doing but Cardiff City's ridiculous owner Vincent Tan has achieved it with his "resign or be sacked" email to Malky Mackay. Tan is expected at Anfield, as is Cardiff's appallingly-treated manager, and will no doubt be incensed if a Liverpool team that can go top of the Premier League are not played off the park by his newly-promoted side. Suárez has scored 11 goals in his last four appearances at Anfield. Tan will probably demand a similar impact from Peter Odemwingie. Andy Hunter

Manchester United have not lost three consecutive home league games since 1979 and after 1-0 defeats to Everton and Newcastle United, they would be mortified with similar against West Ham. Sam Allardyce's side beat Tottenham Hotspur to reach the Capital One Cup semi-finals. That win came at White Harte Lane from a losing position and with Old Trafford less of a fortress now, the visitors will fancy their chances of leaving with something. Jamie Jackson Kick-off Saturday 3pm

A glance at Stoke's next four Premier League games shows how important victory in this one is. Mark Hughes's side play Newcastle and Tottenham Hotspur away from the Britannia Stadium before visits from Everton and Liverpool. Aston Villa might see this as the perfect time for Christian Benteke to break his 11 hours and 59 minutes goal drought in the Premier League. Peter Sharland

Gus Poyet fights slightly shy of describing this as "a must win" fixture for Sunderland but, given their position at the bottom, many Wearsiders would say it is. Chris Hughton, Norwich's manager and a good friend of Poyet's from the days when he coached the Uruguayan at Tottenham, has his own relegation worries but must hope Sunderland are fatigued following their midweek win against Chelsea. Nerves threaten to be frayed well before dusk on an afternoon when Norwich defender Michael Turner returns to his former club. Louise Taylor

West Bromwich Albion's first game of the post-Steve Clarke era sees them take on Hull, with the visitors looking to end a run of three matches without a win. Albion are in poor form too, having lost their lost four matches in a row. They have also lost their two at home to Hull, so the omens are not particularly good for the caretaker manager Keith Downing. Hull have been boosted by the return in defence of James Chester. Peter Sharland

Tottenham Hotspur will be able to judge the qualities of Mauricio Pochettino at first hand on Sundayas Spurs venture to St Mary's hoping to hoist themselves from the doldrums. Pochettino, so impressive since joining Southampton as manager earlier in the year, has had no formal contact as yet from Spurs and is enjoying working under Nicola Cortese at a progressive club which is clearly on the up. "As a manager, what's really important is that the sporting aspect is under my control, in terms of signings," said the Argentinean, who does not envisage much business next month. He seems content. Tottenham are anything but. Dominic Fifield

In-form Everton travel to a Swansea side who have won just twice in front of their own supporters this season. Michael Laudrup's team have won only three times since September, during which last season's top-scorer Michu has gone 676 minutes without a league goal. Roberto Martínez's team are unbeaten since defeat at Manchester City in early October, and victory at the Liberty Stadium may see them spend Christmas in the top four for the first time since 2004. James Dutton

Come kick-off this could actually be a meeting of the teams in third and fifth place, though it still has the ring of a heavyweight occasion. Arsène Wenger, his side so refreshingly resurgent this term, must instigate an immediate recovery after last week's mauling at the Etihad Stadium as he seeks a first win over José Mourinho at the 10th attempt. Chelsea, for their part, are labouring for rhythm at present but will draw encouragement from October's Capital One Cup meeting between the teams, when they won convincingly at the Emirates. Psychological damage can be inflicted on Monday night. The contest feels key. Dominic Fifield

Ole Gunnar Solskjaer makes his home bow as the Cardiff manager and will be looking to build on last week's FA Cup victory at Newcastle against struggling West Ham. Sam Allardyce's side arrive in Wales on the back of maulings against Nottingham Forest and Manchester City and without a league win since November. This is a crucial relegation six-pointer for the visitors and their manager. Max Goldbart

Roberto Martínez has several defensive injury problems with Phil Jagielka and Sylvain Distin both expected to miss out and Leighton Baines doubtful. Fortunately for the Everton manager, the eye-catching emergence of John Stones and the experienced guile of Antolín Alcaraz have more than compensated in recent weeks. Goodison Park will be key to Everton's Champions League prospects in 2014 and they can ill afford a repeat of the Boxing Day slip against Sunderland. For Norwich City, one-time Everton transfer target Leroy Fer returns from a one-match suspension. Andy Hunter

Both these sides have improved since changing manager earlier this season, but only Fulham have managed to clamber out of the bottom three. This is a chance, however, for Gus Poyet's team to haul René Meulensteen's men back into trouble and improve their own chances of survival. Who handles the high stakes better could ultimately determine the outcome of this encounter. Paul Doyle

Sat in midtable at the turn of the year is something Hull could only have dreamed of back on the opening day of the season when they were beaten 2-0 by Chelsea at Stamford Bride. Steve Bruce's side have played with spirit and guile and are well deserving of their place. For Chelsea, a run of five games without defeat in the league should mean they travel to the KC Stadium in confident mood of securing a victory. Max Goldbart

Surely a miserable week for Manchester United cannot end with a second defeat to Swansea City? David Moyes may have a point in citing dodgy luck with refereeing decisions but, as the old adage goes, you make your own fortune in football so the United manager now has to regroup and start the push for a Champions League place by winning for a first time since 28 December, four games ago. Jamie Jackson

The new West Bromwich Albion manager Pepe Mel will be watching from the stands as Keith Downing takes charge of the Midlands side for the last time. The caretaker has impressed and will want to go out on a high against a Southampton team who have lost three of their last four matches. Mauricio Pochettino's men surely view this match as an idea way to get back to winning ways. Max Goldbart

Tottenham Hotspur will presumably still be smarting from last week's rather meek surrender at Arsenal in the FA Cup and, even depleted by injuries, will seek to take frustration out on lowly opponents. Certainly, this seems like an opportunity that can't be missed. Yet Palace have not lost a league game at White Hart Lane since 1980 and have been much improved under Tony Pulis. They will attempt to summon some of the stifling industry which blunted Manchester City recently and hope to pounce on the counter. Dominic Fifield

With Manchester City scoring goals by the bucket load and unbeaten in the league in their last 10 games, you could be forgiven for thinking that this match may be a walk in the park for Manuel Pellegrini's side. However, City's sometimes questionable away form and Newcastle's threat in front of goal suggests otherwise. Tim Krul is likely to return to Alan Pardew's side. Max Goldbart

One statistic stands out: Luis Suárez has scored more Premier League goals than Stoke City this season. The Uruguayan missed the corresponding fixture at Anfield on the opening day, when he was suspended, but he has gone on to rack up 20 goals in 13 appearances. The bad news for Stoke is that Liverpool also have Daniel Sturridge fit again. Stoke, however, have a decent record at home this season and will be encouraged by the fact that Liverpool have never beaten them in the league at the Britannia Stadium. Stuart James

Aston Villa look like obliging opponents for a team of Arsenal's ambitions. Paul Lambert's side have just been knocked out of the FA Cup on their ground by a Sheffield United side currently 18th in League One. They have lost six times already at Villa Park and no other team in the country has managed fewer home goals than their total of seven. Theo Walcott's knee injury has been a grievous setback for Arsenal, making them even more dependent on Olivier Giroud's goals, and Arsène Wenger must decide whether to place his trust in Serge Gnabry, the 18-year-old who impressed against Tottenham Hotspur last weekend. Daniel Taylor

Wretched defeats to Hull and Sunderland in recent weeks have plunged Fulham back into trouble, but they looked like they might be on the right road again having trounced Norwich in the FA Cup. Brede Hangeland made a welcome return from injury in that game and he and his inconsistent team-mates will have to be at their best if Fulham are to have any chance of avoiding another heavy defeat here. Paul Doyle
